guage, and new interpretations of musical compositions that proved influential for their work, Deep Refrains forges the first panoptic view of their writings on music. Gallope concludes that music’s ineffability is neither a conservative phenomenon nor a pious call to silence. Instead, these philosophers ask us to think through the ways in which music’s stunning force might address, in an ethical fashion, intricate philosophical questions specific to the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aMusicxPhilosophy and aesthetics. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAdorno, Theodor.  aAesthetics of Music.  aBloch, Ernst.  aComparative Literature.  aDeleuze, Gilles.  aGuattari, Félix.  aHegel, Georg Wilhelm Friedrich.  aJankélévitch, Vladimir.  aSchopenhauer, Arthur.  aThe Ineffable.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226483726423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226483726/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles